@article{ISI:000332320200015,
 abstract = {Sodium addition is necessary to reach high efficiencies with
Cu(In,Ga)Se-2 (CIGS) solar cells on metallic substrates. This can be
achieved using DC-sputtered multilayer Mo back contacts including a
sodium-doped layer (Mo:Na). In this study, 450 nm-thick Mo:Na layers
were sputter-deposited on Ti foils using a working pressure ranging from
3.4 mTorr to 30 mTorr, and capped with 100 nm-thick, dense, pure Mo
layers. The deposition pressure of the Mo:Na layers strongly affected
their electrical resistance, optical reflectance, morphology, and
crystal quality. The top Mo layer allowed controlling the electrical and
optical properties of the back contact, but its own morphology was
affected by the structure of the underlying Mo:Na layer. The Na
concentration in the CIGS layer varied as a function of the deposition
pressure of the Mo:Na layer, inducing changes in the absorber grain size
and Ga distribution, as well as in the carrier density. Absolute
conversion efficiency improvements over 3% were obtained using the
sodium-doped back contacts on Ti foils, leading to a performance which
was equivalent to the soda-lime glass reference. (C) 2014 AIP Publishing
LLC.},
